Semantic HTML

Without even realising it, we've already been writing "semantic HTML". In fact, in many ways, our goal going forwards is to try and stay as close to these humble beginnings as possible, while we add more complexity.

The old way of adding styling would usually involve adding lots of extra "divs" for styling and presentation, to begin to do layout. But we're using two new and complimentary aspects of the modern web stack to make our pages more readable and robust.

The first of those technologies, which is really just an idea we need to get in our head and stick to, is that HTML elements should tell us what they are. The whole point of 'marking up' content, after all, is to add information to it.

The second piece of technology, which I personally think is a bigger deal than most people have realised, is CSS-Grid.

With CSS Grid, I think we can endeavour to both write and deliver comprehensible, properly structured HTML to people. And then style it, in an efficient and sane way. Or not, if people prefer.
Semantic Elements

The simplest elements of HTML have always been semantic.

Pages have a 'title' block, they have headings and paragraphs (like this one) and they have 'anchor links' (a)... ok, stretching it a bit with that one, but once you've learned it, it always does the right thing.

It used to be the case, though, that there was no good container for most types of content and so they got put into 'generic' divs and spans - those being the default for block and inline content respectively. Once documents started to be littered with lots of these things, there didn't seem to be a big problem adding more, which was handy and even necessary for certain kinds of CSS hacks.

Now, though HTML has proper semantic elements and we 'should' be able to use them for everything, so that it's clear to see, by looking, what each element is meant to be and, equally importantly, the browser has more information about what the parts of the document are.
